1. Add real implementation details (this is the biggest gap)

Right now it sounds conceptual. Make it concrete:

Mention exact setup
Hardware (e.g., laptop specs / cloud VM)
OS and versions
Give actual code-level details
Example CrewAI agent config
Prompt snippets used for MCQ generation
Describe data flow step-by-step
What happens when a student answers a question?

👉 Human papers always show “how it actually works,” not just architecture.

2. Include real results (very important)

Your paper currently has no measurable evaluation, which is a major red flag.

Add:

Table with:
Accuracy of difficulty prediction
Response time analysis
Student score improvements
Compare:
Your system vs static MCQ system

Example:

“Students improved average score from 58% → 72% after adaptive questioning”

👉 Numbers = credibility.

3. Add a small experiment or case study

Even a simple one helps a lot:

10–30 students
Run test with:
Static MCQ vs your adaptive system
Show:
Engagement
Completion rate
Performance

👉 AI-generated papers usually skip real experiments.

4. Reduce “perfect academic tone”

Your current writing is too polished and generic.

Change:

❌ “This paper proposes an adaptive multi-agent system…”
✅ “In our implementation, we built a prototype system using Django and CrewAI…”

Add:

Slightly varied sentence lengths
Occasional simple wording

👉 Humans don’t write like a textbook all the time.

5. Add limitations (very important)

AI-written papers often avoid weaknesses.

Include a section like:

LLM latency issues
Cost of API calls (Gemini)
Possible bias in generated questions
Dependence on prompt quality

👉 This makes it feel real and honest.

6. Make references more grounded

Right now references feel “inserted.”

Improve by:

Connecting each citation clearly:
“Unlike Outay et al. [1], our system does not rely on KPI metrics but instead…”
Avoid generic citation dumping
7. Add figures that match YOUR system

Not generic diagrams — include:

Screenshot of your UI
Flow diagram of your actual pipeline
Agent interaction diagram (based on your implementation)

👉 Visual proof = strong authenticity signal.

8. Personalize technical decisions

Explain why you chose things:

Why Gemini 2.5 Flash?
Why not IRT?
Why CrewAI over AutoGen?

👉 AI text explains “what,” humans explain “why.”

9. Slight imperfection helps

Don’t overdo it, but:

Avoid overly symmetrical paragraphs
Mix short and long sentences
Use natural transitions
